ronics inc in  in the early s with additional franchises and a small field sales organization arrow began selling electronic parts to industrial customers a second storefrontsales office was opened in mineola long island in  by  when the company completed its initial public offering and listed its shares on the american stock exchange total sales amounted to  million over half of which came from the industrial sales division with the remainder from the traditional retail business during the s arrow moved its headquarters to farmingdale new york long island and opened additional branches in norwalk connecticut and totowa new jersey the company relocated its headquarters office to centennial colorado in  in  glenn green  waddell a partnership formed by three recent graduates of the harvard business school b duke glenn jr roger e green and john c waddell led a private investor group that acquired the controlling interest in arrow the investors saw an opportunity to consolidate the fragmented electronics industry duke glenn served as chairman sedit entering the s with  million of annual distribution sales arrow ranked no  among us electronics distributors no ranked avnet was times arrow’s size during the ’s decade by winning key semiconductor franchises led by texas instruments in  and opening sales offices in over  us cities arrow grew its electronics distribution business at an average annual rate of  percent by the end of the decade the company’s electronics distribution sales had climbed to  million making arrow the countrys second largest electronics distributor the company took on high levels of debt through frequent public bond offerings to fund its growth strategy additional growth capital was provided through the  acquisition of schuylkill metals corporation a lead recycling company this business having served its purpose was sold in  amidst problems associated with being designated an epa superfund site contaminated with lead and chromium in the s arrow discontinued its retail operations and inaugurated the electronics distribution’s first integrated online realtime computer system to provide uptotheminute inventory positions and facilitate remote order entry in  arrow was listed on the new york stock exchange the same year it acquired cramer electronics historically the us’s secondlargest distributor the company’s first major industry acquisition which provided access to many markets in the western united states s to presentedit in  a fire in a hotel conference center killed  members of arrow’s senior management including glenn and green waddell assumed leadership and in  recruited stephen p kaufman formerly a partner of mckinsey  company to join arrow as president of the company’s electronics distribution division kaufman succeeded waddell as ceo in  and as chairman in  during his nearly two decades with arrow kaufman led the companys consolidation of the us electronics distribution industry as well as the company’s expansion into europe and the asiapacific region under kaufman’s leadership arrow completed over  acquisitions of electronics distributors including such prominent names as ducommun kierulff lex schweber zeus anthem bell and wyle all in the us spoerle germany silverstar italy and cal hong kong and china kaufman also led the company into the national distribution of commercial computer products initially through its acquisition of gatesfa distributing arrow entered the st century with global sales of  billion— billion of electronic components and  billion of computer products kaufman stepped down as ceo in  retired as chairman in  and was succeeded by daniel w duval a year arrow board veteran in  william e mitchell former president of the global services division of solectron corporation joined arrow as chief executive officer and in  became chairman during mitchell’s six years at arrow sales climbed to  billion as the company increased shareholder returns improved operating efficiencies and completed  acqui